research expedition with a manned vessel  to study <br>
Jupiter, and its moons with special empfasis on Europa.<br>
<br>
 In the real world, this general geophysical research<br>
at Jupiter was actually done by the Galileo robot orbiter spacecraft that was sent to Jupiter . Now the Cassini robot<br>
Orbiter spacecraft  is on its way to Saturn to perform a <br>
similar mission there.<br>
<br>
 We could have launched manned expeditions instead<br>
of robotic ones to Jupiter and Saturn Like in the movies.<br>
We have technology enough to make it easy to send a <br>
manned spaceship to any of the 9 planets, if we choose<br>
to use it.This has been true for 30 - 40 years<br>
<br>
 Manned spaceflight to the planets is best done using nuclear<br>
powered, and nuclear propelled spacecraft.<br>
<br>
 We have however always sent chemical propelled robot probes to the planets instead of crewed vessels.<br>
Why has this been the case? Why robot probes instead<br>
of crewed vessels to the planets.?<br>
<br>
There are some reasons for these things:<br>
<br>
 1. Manned spaceflight is very  dangerous, to the crews<br>
 who go on a Journey to anywhere in space.<br>
2.It costs 10,000 dollars a pound to launch anything into leo to begin a space flight with chemical rocketry.<br>
3. A robotic space probe with for example a mass of <br>
1000 kilograms costs 22,000,000 dollars to just put <br>
it in leo even if it has advanced terminal stage propulsion<br>
after arriving in leo.<br>
4. If we launched a crewed vessel to a planet we must <br>
provide enough life support resources to keep them alive<br>
for years. If we launched a crewed vessel to a planet <br>
from leo with a mass of 1,000,000 kilograms it will cost<br>
at least 22,000,000,000 dollars just to put it in leo.<br>
5.This assumes the use of advanced propulsion.<br>
If chemical propulsion is used the required vessel<br>
 will have to have a lift off  mass that is about 3 times <br>
this amount   in leo. That is about 3,000,000 kilograms. <br>
This will  cost 66,000,000,000 dollars to put it in leo.<br>
This is because of the rocket eqaution, and its resulting<br>
mass ratio requirements for low specific impulse chemical<br>
fuels..<br>
5. Ever wonder where that 50,000,000,000 price tag<br>
for a singled Manned Mars mission came from back in the <br>
1990s.? This is the source of it.<br>
6. You are also aware of the political opposition to nuclear<br>
spaceflght.<br>
7.The U.S. congress has refused to fund any manned <br>
lunar or interplanetary missions since the 1970s because<br>
of the price tag for them, and because of the need to use<br>
nuclear propulsion on them.<br>
8. For The U.S congress the federal budget is one big pork barrel to buy votes in their district.The military industrial<br>
complex is more powerful politicaly then any other group.<br>
For example Bush and Congress want to spend <br>
600,000,000,000 dollars to invade Iraq.We could build an entire fleet of nuclear powered, and reusable manned interplanetary spacecraft with those monies et el.<br>
9. The liberals on the other end want to spend,<br>
the same 600,000,000,000 dollars on social welfare<br>
programs, to buy other votes in their congressional <br>
district.They do not want to spend it on space flight.<br>
10. The private sector has technological resources enough<br>
for manned interplanetary spaceflight. But at chemical rocket<br>
launch costs of 10,000 dollars a pound the private space carriers  can not afford it. Also private business Is <br>
interested in only short term profits, low risks,and the short term bottom line on their monetary  budget.<br>
11. Private Space flight except for commercial satallite launches,  and suborbital/orbital tourism for the super rich does  not meet the above criteria for the private sector.<br>
12. Even those few private persons and families that<br>
may have scientific, and technological knowledge enough<br>
to achieve private space flight of some kind, simply can not<br>
afford it unless they are are them selves super rich <br>
centi-milllionaires or billionaires et el.<br>
13. This why Humans have never journeyed beyond the moon<br>
in person et el, and why we have not returned to the moon since 1973 with a crewed expedition.<br>
