<br>
Even though I certainly support sending manned missions throughout the solar system purely on the ground that it will drive the technological developments we need for living in space, I question the raw need to develop manned spacecraft for purely scientific ventures to the outer planets.  It seems to me you could outfit a robotic craft with a lot of probes, landers, sample return capabilities, etc, for the price of sending a manned mission.  I think with developments in computing and artificial intelligence, it may prove ultimately uneconomical to send people in the place of robotic craft for doing purely science missions.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>10. The private sector has technological resources enough<br>
for manned interplanetary spaceflight. But at chemical rocket<br>
launch costs of 10,000 dollars a pound the private space carriers can not afford it. Also private business Is <br>
interested in only short term profits, low risks,and the short term bottom line on their monetary budget.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I believe private sector involvement in space will slowly evolve, and that it will evolve in a direction that is consumerate with setting up communities in space.  There are a lot of plans on the drawing boards for things like orbital resorts, hotels on the moon, etc.  These things are out of reach for the mean time but some companies are seriously pursuing them.  We might eventually start seeing things like retirement homes in orbit, etc.  This is where I think a lot of the drive for manned spaceflight should go, toward the development of communities in space.  Even if we can't make use of nuclear propulsion because of red tape, perhaps technologies like the space elevator will prove themselves effective and allow the lowcost access needed for space colonization.   To be brutally honest, the scientific research aspects of spaceflight don't interest me nearly as much as setting up communities off of Earth.  And I absolutely couldn't agree more with points 8 and 9.  I want to get off this planet just to escape bad government.  I think a space colony could pretty much operate in a very anarchist mode (don't confuse this with chaos) for a variety of reasons.      <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 389<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/21/03 3:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=152.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: manned spaceflight Versus robotics</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; I question the raw need to develop manned 